Leo J. Hindery Jr.President and Chief Executive Officer, TCI Pacific Communications, Inc.AgeTotal Calculated CompensationThis person is connected to 17 Board Members in 17 different organizations across 27 different industries.See Board Relationships69--
Background

		Mr. Leo J. Hindery, Jr. is Founder and Co-Managing Partner InterMedia Advisors, LLC. Mr. Hindery serves as the Chief Executive Officer and President of TCI Pacific Communications, Inc. He is Founder and Co-Managing Partner of Intermedia Partners VII, L.P.; and InterMedia Partners, LP. He is Managing Partner of InterMedia Partners, LLC, a series of media industry investment funds he founded in 1988. He serves as the President and Chairman of HL Capital. He was Co-Founder ... of Journalism Online, LLC and Piano Inc. He was a Venture Partner at Allegis Capital. In 2008, he was an economic and trade advisor to presidential candidate Barack Obama. Previously, he served as the Chairman and Chief Executive Officer of Yankees Entertainment & Sports Network, LLC (The YES Network) from 2001 to October 2004. From February 2001 to August 2001, he was an independent businessman. He served as Chief Executive Officer of Level 3 GC Limited from March 2000 to October 2000. From December 1999 to January 2001, he served as the Chairman and Chief Executive Officer of GlobalCenter, Inc. From February 1997 to November 1999, he served as the President and Chief Executive Officer of AT&T's Broadband & Internet Services and Comcast Cable Holdings, LLC (also known as Tele-Communications). He served as the President of ClarkTel Tele-Communications, Inc. He served as Chief Executive Officer & President of TCIC at Tele-Communications International, Inc. since March 1997. He served as Chief Operating Officer - TCI at Tele-Communications International, Inc. March 1997. From 1985 to 1988, he was the Chief Officer for Planning and Finance of The Chronicle Publishing Company. Before this, Mr. Hindery served as the Chief Financial Officer and Managing Director of Becker Paribas, Inc., from 1983 to 1985. He began in 1971 with Utah International, Inc. where he served as its Senior Financial Officer. He served as the Chairman of Teach For America, Inc. He served as Vice Chairman of Asia Global Crossing Ltd. He served as the Chairman of GT Group Telecom, Inc. since September 18, 2001. Mr. Hindery serves as Vice Chairman of Gemini Networks, Inc. and zUniversity.com, Inc. He serves as a Member of Board of Advisors at Illume Software, Inc. Mr. Hindery serves as a Director of Daniels Fund, International Radio & Television Society Foundation, Inc., the Library of Congress Trust Fund, Victory Junction, IDT Telecom, Inc., Outpost.com, TD Ameritrade, Inc. (also known as TD Waterhouse Group, Inc.) and Gemini Networks, Inc. He has been a Director of General Motors Company since June 6, 2017. He has been a Director of Cellular Spyware, Inc. (PhoneGuard, Inc) since December 2011. He serves as a Member of Advisory Board at Global Locate, Inc. and Democracy Radio. He serves as a Trustee at Citizens Budget Commission. He has been a Director of Hemisphere Media Group, Inc. since April 2013. He serves as a Director of Teach For America, Inc. He serves as a Member of the Advisory Board at Gephardt Group, LLC. Mr. Hindery served as a Member of the Advisory Board at Polaris Partners (also known as Polaris Venture Partners, Inc.). He served as a Director of OneMediaPlace, Inc., Akamai Technologies, Inc., Keynote Systems, Inc., Tanning Technology Corporation, DirecTV Broadband, Inc., BravoSolution US, Inc. (also known as Verticalnet Inc.), Global Crossing Ltd., GlobalCenter, At Home Corporation, TV Guide Inc., and Utah International Inc. He served as a Director of GT Group Telecom, Inc. since March 23, 2000. He served as a Director of Options Media Group Holdings, Inc. since December 14, 2011 and Tele-Communications International, Inc. since April 1998. He served as a Non-Executive Director of Moko Social Media Limited from April 1, 2015 to April 14, 2016. He served as a Director of Comcast Cable Holdings, LLC and Center for Communication, Inc. He serves as Director of Common Cause New York, the Jesuit School of Theology of Santa Clara University and the Minority Media and Telecommunications Council. He is a Co-Chair of the Task Force on Job Creation and Trade and was the founder of Jobs First 2012. He is a member of ‘Jobs for New Yorkers’ and Council on Foreign Relations. In 1998, Mr. Hindery was an International Cable Executive of the year and he received the Foundation Award of the International Radio & Television Society, the Executive Achievement Award of the National Association of Minorities in Cable, the CTPAA President's Award for Outstanding Commitment to Public Affairs and the Joel A. Berger Award for his leadership in AIDS and HIV awareness and initiatives. In 1999, he was named Cable Television Operator of the Year and was named by “Business Week” as one of the “Top 25 Executives of the Year”. In 2002, Mr. Hindery was inducted into the Hall of Fame of the Minority Media and Telecom Council and he received the Oakes-Shrum Leadership Award of the Gay & Lesbian Victory Fund. Mr. Hindery was named in 2002 as a “Founder of the Society of Jesus (Jesuits)”. In 2003, he co-founded, along with Russian Federation Council Chairman Sergey Mironov, Transatlantic Partners against AIDS (TPAA). In 2004, Mr. Hindery received The Chapel of Four Chaplains Legion of Honor Award for service to humanity. In 2005, he received from the Asia Society and TPAA their Founders Award for his efforts in the international fight against AIDS, notably in Asia. Mr. Hindery was Chairman of the National Cable Television Association and of C-SPAN, has been recognized as one of the cable industry’s “25 Most Influential Executives over the Past 25 Years” and one of the “30 Individuals with the Most Significant Impact on Cable's Early History”. Mr. Hindery is the author of “It Takes a CEO: It’s Time to Lead With Integrity (Free Press, 2005) and The Biggest Game of All” (Free Press, 2003). He has received honorary doctorate of Humane Letters degrees from each of Emerson College and the Rabbinical College of America. Mr. Hindery received an MBA from Stanford University Graduate School of Business in 1971 and is a graduate, with honors, from Seattle University.Read Full Background




